content.problemStatement:
In the C programming language, a structure is a user-defined data type that allows you to group together variables of different data types under a single name. \
Each variable within a structure is referred to as a "member" or "field".

**Structure declaration:** To define a structure, you use the **`struct`** keyword followed by the structure name and a list of member variables enclosed in curly braces. \
Sample syntax:
```c
struct MyStruct {
    // Members (variables) of the structure
    type member1;
    type member2;
    // ...
};
```
**Initializing a Structure:** You can initialize a structure at the time of declaration by providing values for its member variables.  \
Sample syntax:
```c
struct StructName variableName = { value1, value2, ... };
```
**Accessing Structure Members:** You can access the members of a structure using the dot (`.`) operator. \
Sample syntax:
```c
variableName.memberName
```

